    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Metro-North Should Let Riders Voice Their Opinions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gary I Rosen letter on August 13 article describes how Metro-North might improve its newsletter, Mileposts (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Mileposts really misses the train.</p>
        <p>I had hoped your article [''Revealed: The Wry Voice of Metro-North,'' Aug. 13] on Joseph Antonacci might explain why Metro-North seems so out of touch with its riders. Mileposts proves monthly how off track Metro-North is with its commuters. Perhaps it can accomplish its same goals by putting more effort into giving voice to all the real humor and legitimate news occurring daily on the trains: a community on rails.</p>
        <p>We have shared stories, unspoken rules and observations on where we sit, how to use a cell phone politely and an unlimited vocabulary of commuter body language.</p>
        <p>Mileposts, if you want to toot your horn about your on-time performance, give us a monthly voice, too. You might even be able to sell some advertising to cover your costs.</p>
        <p>GARY I. ROSEN  Scarsdale</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
